# Governance policy for the support-triage workflow (DR-0028 governance DSL).
#
# This labels the REAL data sources in the environment — not variables in any
# whip. IT signs this once; users then author whips freely and the compiler holds
# them to it.
#
# Two axes per resource:
#   readable by <Role>  — confidentiality: who is cleared to READ this data.
#   from <Role>         — integrity: whose vouching is required to WRITE it.
# `public` is the bottom of both: world-readable / untrusted.

# The CRM holds customer PII. Only a party acting for Operator may read it, and
# only Operator-vouched data may be written into it.
grant file_store crm -> file:/srv/crm.db readable by Operator from Operator

# Inbound email lands here as files. It is attacker-controllable: world-readable
# (no secrets) and UNtrusted (public integrity — anyone could have sent it).
grant file_store inbox -> maildir:/var/mail/support readable by public from public

# The public reply channel goes back to the (untrusted) customer.
grant channel public_reply -> smtp:out readable by public from public

# Our in-house model is cleared to see Operator data; sending a turn's context to
# it is not egress. (The provider is keyed by the agent's `provider` identifier.)
grant provider fixture -> selfhost:llama readable by Operator from Operator

# An append-only event log of untrusted inbound activity (public, untrusted-OK).
grant file_store audit_log -> file:/srv/audit.log readable by public from public

# A recorded fact derived from CRM is Operator-only: only cleared subscribers of
# the fact-base / session-event stream may read it (H2 -- record is a governed sink).
grant factbase fact:Reviewed -> internal:reviewed readable by Operator from Operator
